2026-04-21 02:37:51 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 1 LED', 'Control module 2 LED', 'Control module 3 LED', 'Control module 4 LED', 'Control module 5 LED', 'Control module 6 LED', 'Control module 7 LED', 'Control module 8 LED'] hypothesis_explanation='The control module indicator LEDs in modules 1–8 are physically missing from the circuit. This means each module has an open circuit at the LED indicator position when the switch is ON. Since the main series path in each control module is through the switch contacts and not the parallel LED indicator branch, the absence of these indicator LEDs should not prevent normal series circuit function—assuming the switches themselves are intact and properly closed. However, if the LED indicator branch was in series with the switch or constituted the only internal path, it could create an open circuit, breaking continuity and preventing current from reaching the load module and therefore turning on the main lamp. Given the visual schematic, it appears the main current should still flow through the closed switch. Given all control module LEDs are absent and assuming the schematic accurately represents the switch/LED arrangement, the most plausible remaining root cause is that the missing LEDs, due to their method of mounting, physically interrupt the connection even for the main current path. The missing LEDs thus render the circuit open at every control module, breaking the circuit to the load.'
